50|$|The Security Council was {{concerned}} about large-scale illegal arms trafficking in Africa, particularly of small arms and the threat it posed to security, development and humanitarian situation on the continent. In this regard, African countries were urged to introduce legislation {{on the use of}} arms. Member States, particularly those that manufactured weapons, were reminded of the importance of restricting <b>arms</b> <b>transfers</b> which could provoke or prolong armed conflicts. The resolution encouraged African states to participate in the United Nations Register of <b>Conventional</b> <b>Arms</b> and to establish regional and subregional registers to enhance the transparency of <b>arms</b> <b>transfers.</b> They were also instructed to look to the European Union and Organization of American States for their efforts in tackling the arms trade and to adopt similar measures.|$|R
50|$|Before joining UNSCOM, Duelfer was Deputy Assistant Secretary of State {{for arms}} control and {{multilateral}} defense matters. From 1990 to 1992, {{he was in charge}} of defense trade matters as the director of the Center for Defense Trade and Deputy to the Assistant Secretary of State for politico-military affairs. In this capacity, he had responsibility for <b>arms</b> <b>transfers,</b> munitions licensing, and <b>conventional</b> <b>arms</b> control. From January to March 1991, he directed the State Department's Task Force in support of Operation Desert Storm.|$|R
40|$|Sorry, {{the full}} text of this article is not {{available}} in Huskie Commons. Please click on the alternative location to access it. 209 p. Transfers of sophisticated weaponry to developing countries have several consequences, one of which is the dependence of a recipient upon its suppliers. Dependence is defined as a structural situation characterized by a concentration of linkages in the absence of alternatives. In a dependent <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> relationship, the recipient relies upon single or predominant suppliers. Dependence in <b>arms</b> <b>transfers</b> has led some developing countries to adopt one or both of two strategies to counter their foreign arms-transfer dependence. The first strategy is to diversify arms sources from largely single to multiple sources. The second strategy is to develop domestic defense industries. This study assesses the results of those counter-dependence strategies as implemented by the six members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) [...] Brunei, Indonesia, the Philippines, Malaysia, Singapore, and Thailand. Four major questions are explored: (1) Does <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> dependence actually exist between ASEAN countries and their arms suppliers? (2) To what extent have ASEAN nations implemented strategies to diversify arms sources and achieved self-reliance? (3) What are the results of those counter-dependence strategies? and (4) Has the structure of <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> dependence between ASEAN states and their supplying nations changed?In this research, a comparative case study of the <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> structure of six individual ASEAN nations was conducted. The Herfindahl Index was employed to assess the concentration of linkages and determine changes in transfer structure for those countries from 1951 to 1990. Weapons production capacity and capability were assessed with Robert Harkavy's production capacity ranking and Andy Lee Ross's <b>Conventional</b> <b>Arms</b> Production Coefficients. The data indicate that <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> dependence exists between each of the six ASEAN members and their arms suppliers. Some degree of supply diversification occurred in every ASEAN nation but the attempts to alter their concentrated arms supply structures have not led to any sustained reductions in <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> dependence. The data also indicate that strategies which promote domestic arms production simply transform <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> dependence into a dependence on foreign technology...|$|R
50|$|The U/S {{also leads}} the interagency policy process on nonproliferation and manages global U.S. {{security}} policy, principally {{in the areas}} of nonproliferation, arms control, regional security and defense relations, and <b>arms</b> <b>transfers</b> and security assistance. The U/S provides policy direction in the following areas: nonproliferation, including the missile and nuclear areas, as well as chemical, biological, and <b>conventional</b> weapons proliferation; <b>arms</b> control, including negotiation, ratification, verification and compliance, and implementation of agreements on strategic, non-conventional, and conventional forces; regional security and defense relations, involving policy regarding U.S. security commitments worldwide {{as well as on the}} use of U.S. military forces in unilateral or international peacekeeping roles; and <b>arms</b> <b>transfers</b> and security assistance programs and <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> policies.|$|R
