40|$|Through {{a careful}} {{examination}} of French <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> behavior {{over the past}} twenty years, this article attempts to {{contribute to the development of}} a more open, accurate, and reliable system for collecting <b>arms</b> <b>transfer</b> data and for evaluating the military, political, economic, and technological impact of <b>arms</b> <b>transfers</b> on international security. Part one presents <b>arms</b> <b>transfers</b> data for deliveries and orders for France since 1956 based on open French governmental sources. Part two contrasts these findings with ACDA figures. ACDA would appear to substantially underestimate French transfers in constant and current dollars. From 1966 to 1975, these amount, respectively, to $ 1750 million and $ 5003 million. Part three outlines some of the principal implications of the two sets of conflicting data for estimating French <b>arms</b> <b>transfers.</b> In contrast to ACDA findings, French economic dependency on <b>arms</b> <b>transfers</b> is considerable and increasing. Until this dependence can be decreased and associated strategic and domestic political restraints relaxed, there exists little French interest in the immediate future in international efforts, such as those of the Carter administration, to diminish the magnitude, rate, or level of sophistication of <b>arms</b> <b>transfers</b> and technological know-how. World Military Expenditures and <b>Arms</b> <b>Transfers,</b> the annual publi-cation of the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency, has become the lingua franca of researchers and practitioners concerned with arms control and <b>arms</b> <b>transfers.</b> That they have strong incentives to rely on AUTHOR’S NOTE: This article was supported by a grant from the Ford Foundation under terms of its competition in international security and arms control. The findings and opinions expressed in it are solely those of the author. Richard Grimmett’s criticisms are also gratefully acknowledge